1. d4 f5
{ Here is a more detailed list what this course covers and what is left out.  - 2. c4, 2. Nf3 and 2. g3   These moves will be covered in a separate course aimed only at Leningrad Dutch players. There is very little overlap after these moves for Leningrad Dutch  (Nf6, g6, Bg7, d6)  , classical Dutch  (Nf6, e6, d6, Be7)  and Stonewall  (Nf6, e6, d5, c6, Bd6)  players.   - 2. Nc3   Here I cover the 2... Nf6 3.Bg5 d5 system. It is Black's best answer to 2.Nc3. In the 4. Bxf6 line I chose not to cover the popular setup with Nc6 and Qd7 but the not so well-know but equally good setup with c6 which as far as I know has not been properly covered in any of the books I have read. Usually only a few lines are given in which Black played at least one dubious move.   - 2. Bf4   Against this move I chose to give two completely different setups. One close in spirit to the Leningrad Dutch and one resembling the classical Dutch.   The system based on the Leningrad Dutch is a bit risky if White chooses the Bf4, e3, Nc3 move order and plays h4 as soon as Black plays g6. The problem is that in order to avoid the dangerous exchange sacrifice h5 Nxh5, Rxh5 which gives White a strong attack, Black is forced to lose a tempo with h6 which also weakens the square g6. I still play this system exclusively but I could not give this system as the only repertoire choice with a clean conscience.  The system based on the classical Dutch is solid and likely the reason why 2. Bf4  (without an early Nf3)  is not more popular among stronger players.   - 2. e4, the Staunton Gambit  The Staunton Gambit is covered in two chapters. The first covers the slightly dubious 4. g4 and the harmless 4. f3 system. The most challenging move 4. Bg5 is covered in a separate chapter. I chose 4...g6 as the repertoire move. It is less popular than 4... Nc6 but in my opinion at least as good. Here studying the lines with 5.h4 is important.   - 2. Bg5   There are two good answers to 2.Bg5, 2...g6 and 2...h6 followed by g5. The first is solid but has quite a bit of theory and a number of tricky transpositions while the second is a bit more risky but playable and currently my main choice. Here I would make sure that I remember the key lines and key ideas in the 4.e4 system because Black's positions tend to be a bit dangerous in exchange for the piece White is forced to sacrifice for some, but probably insufficient, compensation.  - 2. e3 and 2. c3   These moves are not covered because    - concrete analysis is difficult because there are too many transpositions     - almost always Nf3 is played very soon    - pretty much every sensible setup for Black equalizes.   My suggestion is to play any setup you like to play in the Dutch  (I play either the Leningrad with an early Nc6 to prepare e5, or a Queen's Indian setup with Nf6, e6, Be7, b6 and Bb7)  and take it from there.   - 2. h3   Here I only consider lines starting with 2. h3 Nf6 3. g4 because after other moves White is simply a tempo down on regular lines with the possible exception of some lines in the Bf4 systems. The repertoire choice is 3...d5 after which White tends to be a bit behind in development.  - 2. g4   Actually, more reasonable than it may look at first sight and rather popular among stronger players. Here I suggest to take on g4 but ignore a subsequent h3 to avoid opening lines on the kingside. Black should quickly develop here with Nf6, Nc6 and aim for castling queenside.  - 2. Qd3   Here I give two options, the surprising 2... Nc6 and going for a Stonewall. I play 2... Nc6 since I learned about this move. But since White can force Black to sacrifice a piece for sufficient compensation with 3. Qxf5 I propose the Stonewall as a safe alternative. The white queen is misplaced on d3 in the Stonewall. Unfortunately, there is no reasonable way for Black to go for a Leningrad setup against 2. Qd3.  - 2. Nh3   Here I suggest g6 which will very likely transpose to the mainlines in the Leningrad Dutch after g3 and Bg2. Attempts by White to avoid such a transposition are discussed in this short chapter. If you prefer the classical Dutch or the Stonewall then 2... e6 is also perfectly fine. The flexible move 2... Nf6 is possible but it gives White the independent option 3. Bg5 which is discussed in the introduction to the chapter on 2. Nh3.  - 2. h4  This move is not covered here. 2. h4 is a good move if Black chooses a Leningrad setup. But against a classical Dutch or a Stonewall it is at best a loss of a tempo. I probably would try to play a Stonewall without c6, castle long and try to open lines against the white king with h6 and g5  (in case White castles kingside)  .  - 1. Nf3 f5  A chapter I added because the beta-testers told me to do so. Here I discuss the move 2.d3 aiming for a quick e4 which can be dangerous if Black is unprepared. }
