1. Nf3 f5 2. d3 { The most dangerous of the attempts to avoid the mainlines. }
2... d6
{ This was my choice for a while but I no longer believe that Black can equalize  (or get a sufficiently interesting position) }
3. e4
{ The critical move. Other moves like 3. g3 or 3. c4 will usually transpose to Dutch or English main lines. }
3... e5 4. Nc3
{ 4.exf5  is not dangerous. Black has at least equality after  4...Bxf5  5.d4  e4  6.Ng5  Nf6  7.f3  otherwise Black is better after h6  7...exf3  8.Nxf3  d5  9.Be2  Bd6  10.O-O  O-O =  Black has a slight lead in development but will lose a tempo with his bishop on f5. }
4... c5
{ Stopping d4. Kindermann calls this 'another rather desperate suggestion' but Malaniuk and Moskalenko endorse it.   4...Nf6  5.exf5  Bxf5  6.d4  is better for White because  6...e4 ?!  7.Nh4  is good for White. The black queen does not cover h4 any longer after Nf6 has been played.   4...Nc6  5.exf5  Bxf5  6.d4  is also better for White, because after  6...e4 ?!  7.d5  is possible  7...exf3  8.dxc6  bxc6  9.Qxf3  and White is clearly better. }
5. g3 { 5.Bg5  Be7  is fine for Black } 5... Nc6 6. Bh3
{ Malaniuk considers several moves in this position but does not mention Kindermann's suggestion 6. Bh3 which is the reason why I don't feel comfortable suggesting 2... d6. The point is that White can exchange the light-squared bishops leaving Black in an uphill struggle for equality. The funny thing is that engines do not seem to appreciate this line but Black managed only one draw in the 6 human games I could find. }
6... fxe4 7. Bxc8 Qxc8
{ preparing Qh3 and keeping the option to castle queenside alive. White's position does not look very impressive but I don't think Black has any promising long term plans and permanent weaknesses on d5 and e6. The pawn on d6 may also look weak but it is not so easy to attack. }
8. dxe4
{ If Black tries   8...Qh3  White can simply play  9.Be3  preparing to castle queenside. White has a small but long lasting advantage. }
