1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6
{ Black wants to play the typical Leningrad moves next: d6, g6, Bg7 and O-O. One problem is that as long as White does not play Nf3 and block the path of the queen to h5 the attack with h2-h4-h5 is quite dangerous for Black. Black has the following options:   - play d6 and g6 anyway and answer h4 with h6 to be ready to answer h5 with g5   - play d6 and then e6 first and if White plays Nf3 then play g6, Bg7 and Qe7   - play e6, Be7, b6, Bb7 and perhaps a5, Na6 in the spirit of the Queen's Indian.   I have played all three setups without having a clear favorite. Here I am suggesting to play g6 as soon as possible. Mostly because it is the most flexible option if White plays an early Nf3. }
3. e3
{ 3.Nc3  This move poses the biggest problem if Black wants to use a Leningrad setup. The safest move here is e6. The idea is to fight for the square e4 with Bb4 and if White stops this with a3 then Black can switch to a classical Dutch with d6, or play a6 to stop Nb5 and then play d5 and c5 giving Black a good game. This is the option I suggest if you find the system suggested in this chapter too risky. Since the most straightforward move g6 is too dangerous I suggest to play the semi-waiting move d6 before committing to a Leningrad setup. If White plays Nf3 next then g6 is fine. If White continues to prepare g6 with h4 then we have to give up on g6, or at least postpone it.  3...d6   3...g6 ?!  This is move simply does not work here.  4.h4  Simple and strong.  4...h6 ?!  Often a good move with the intention of answering h5 with g5. Unfortunately here it fails because g6 is weak.   4...d6  Allowing h5 in the Dutch after g6 has been played is often dangerous. Here it leads to a clear advantage for White.  5.h5  Nxh5  6.Rxh5  An exchange sacrifice every Leningrad player needs to be aware of. Usually there is no quick mate but White's attack almost plays itself: e3, Qxh5, Nf3, O-O-O, Bc4, Rh1 etc.  6...gxh5  7.e3  is very dangerous for Black.   4...Bg7  The comments after d6 apply verbatim.  5.h5  Nxh5  6.Rxh5  gxh5  7.e3  5.Qd3 !  The refutation.  5...d6   5...Bg7  6.Qg3 !  with a double attack on c7 and g6.  6.e4  Black's position is just awful.  4.h4   4.e3  g6  transposes to 3. e3 g6   4.Qd2  does not make much sense here.  4...Nbd7  5.O-O-O  preventing e5  5...c6  with b5 to follow looks unpleasant for White.  4...e6  This can lead to positions resembling the classical Dutch but where White's h4 is not really useful.  5.e3  Qe7 !?  with the idea Nc6 and e5 is interesting and my suggestion if you look for something unusual.   5...Be7  6.Nf3  O-O  This is the sensible choice and gives an improved version of the classical Dutch. I would probably fianchetto my bishop next and then decide where to put the knight.  6.Nf3  Nc6  followed by Bd7 and the perhaps e5. But since White hasn't really shown his hand yet waiting for a few moves with a6, g6 and h6 is also possible. I would keep the decision in which direction to castle open as long as possible. }
3... g6 4. h4
{ 4.Nc3  d6  5.h4   5.Bc4  e6  Closing the bishop diagonal. Black plans to continue with Bg7, Qe7, O-O and Nc6. Often after the king has moved to h8 or h7, in case h7-h6 has been played, Black plays e5 as well.  6.Nf3  Bg7  7.O-O  Qe7  is about equal   5.Nf3  Bg7  6.d5  Probably too ambitious. White stops Nc6 and e6 and hopes to exploit the weakened e6 square.  6...O-O  7.Bc4  h6  stopping Ng5 and preparing an escape for the king.  8.O-O  Kh7  followed by c6. Black is a bit better since White's pieces, especially the bishops, do not have any targets but rather are targets themselves. Black, on the other hand has the clear plan of expanding on the queenside with c6, b5 and perhaps b4 and Qb6.  5...h6  transposes to 4. h4 h6 5. Nc3 d6.   4.Bc4  Bg7  5.Nd2  e6  as before the bishop diagonal should be closed. Black can still decide whether to go for a queen's indian setup with b6 and Bb7 or to play O-O, Kh8, Nc6, d6, Qe7 and e5.  6.c3  O-O  7.h4  Nc6  with mutual chances. }
4... h6
{ 4...d6  5.h5  is another variation of the exchange sacrifice.  5...Nxh5   5...Bg7  6.h6  is good for White.  6.Rxh5  gxh5  7.Qxh5+  Kd7  8.Qxf5+  is good for White.   4...Bg7  5.h5  and by now you know the rest. }
5. Nc3
{ White has another option which may lead to a small plus.   5.Nh3  d6  6.Bg3  Nh5  allowing Nf4 and h4-h5 is not pleasant for Black.  7.Bh2  Bg7  8.Be2  O-O  Black sacrifices a pawn for speedy development.  9.Bxh5  gxh5  10.Qxh5  e5  11.Nc3   11.dxe5  dxe5  gives Black compensation for the pawn since the pile-up of White's pieces on the h-file does not make much sense without control over the square f4.  11...exd4  Black regains the pawn but gives White control over f4.  12.exd4  Qe8+  13.Qe2  Bxd4  14.O-O-O  Qxe2  15.Nxe2  Bg7  is playable but more comfortable for White. }
5... d6 6. Qf3
{ Demuth gave this position as the reason for prefering 3... e6 against 3. Nc3. He may be right but matters are far from simple.   6.Bd3  White plans to open the center with e4 which would expose the weak pawn on g6.  6...Nc6  A good response. Black prepares e5 and plans to answer e4 with Nb4 and a subsequent exf5 with Nxd3+ and Bxf5.  7.Nf3  Bg7  This position is roughly balanced. Black plans to castle next. }
6... Nc6
{ Black plans to complete his development with e6, Qe7, Bg7 and either O-O or Bd7 and O-O-O. The move e5 is also always a possibility. White has three main moves here. Attack g6 with Qg3, disrupt Black's plan immediately or castle queenside to wait for Black's next move. }
7. d5
{ Probably not the strongest move but nonetheless critical. If Black cannot defend here then the system has to be abandoned.   7.O-O-O  A logical move but now Black can prevent d5 with e6.  7...e6  8.Bc4   8.e4  may cause problems for Black  Qe7  9.Qg3  Rg8  10.Kb1  Bd7 =   7.Qg3  If Black has already put the bishop on g7 then Kf7 is the only option. But here we can also play the simpler Rg8.  7...Rg8  8.O-O-O   8.d5  Nb4  9.O-O-O  e5  10.dxe6  Bxe6  is fine for Black  11.Bb5+  c6  12.Bxd6  Qa5  13.Qe5  looks scary but Black is fine after  13...Kf7  14.Bd3  Nxa2+  15.Nxa2  Qxa2  16.Bxf8  Rgxf8  8...e6  Black plans to continue with Qe7, Bd7 and O-O-O with a balanced position. }
7... Nb4 { wins a tempo. } 8. O-O-O Bg7
{ A bit surprising since Rg8 is no longer effective. The point here is that White has castled queenside already and has opened the long diagonal for the bishop. }
9. Qg3 O-O { Kf7 is also possible but I prefer O-O here. } 10. a3
{ 10.Qxg6  Ng4  The point. Because White castled already f2 is hanging and the white queen is in trouble after Rf6, Bd7 and Be8. }
10... a5 { Another move which is fun to play. } 11. axb4 axb4 12. Nb1 Ne4
{ Black has a strong attack which gives him enough compensation for the piece. White will have trouble to untangle the pieces on the kingside. A likely continuation is   13.Qxg6  Rf6  14.Qh5  Nxf2  and Black is better after taking on h1. }
