1. d4 f5 2. Qd3
{ Black faces the usual quandary: should he try to find a way to go for a Leningrad-like position with g6, Nf6, and d6, or bail out and choose either a classical Dutch setup with Nf6, e6, d6, Be7, O-O, or a Stonewall setup with d5, e6, Nf6, Bd6 and O-O.  First, let's look at the usual Leningrad moves: after 2... Nf6 3. Qxf5 Black does not get much if any compensation for the pawn, 2... g6 gives White a strong attack after 3. h4, and 2... d6 allows 3. Nc3 and now Back has to either lose a tempo with 3... d5, or allow White to play e4 after say Nf6 with a good position for White.  If you like classical Dutch positions then 2... e6 should be fine as well although I don't like Black's position after   2.Qd3  e6  3.g4  fxg4  4.h3  g3  5.Qxg3.   If you like Stonewall positions then 2... d5 is a good choice. The queen on d3 is not well-placed for the standard anti-Stonewall maneuvers. This option is the topic of another chapter. }
2... Nc6
{ This interesting move was suggested by Demuth. It has already been played in one GM game. The attempts to punish it   3.d5  and   3.Qxf5  lead to unique positions in which Black is doing well.   3.g4  is also harmless.  If White tries to steer into calmer waters with   3.Nf3  or   3.g3  the best moves in my opinion, then Black can still go for Leningrad structures with e6, Nf6 followed by g6, Bg7 and O-O. Compared to the standard Leningrad positions Black spent an extra move on e6 and played an early Nc6 while White played Qd3. I must admit I am not sure who profits from these extra moves. }
3. Qxf5
{ The critical move because it forces Black to offer a  (correct)  piece sacrifice. White has a few alternatives.     3.Nf3  e6  preventing d5   3...d6  4.d5  Ne5  5.Nxe5  dxe5  6.e4  seems to be better for White.  4.g3  the only GM game in this line went   4.e4  Nb4  5.Qe2  fxe4  6.Qxe4  Nf6  7.Qe2  c5  and Black was already a bit better.  Nf6  5.Bg2  g6  6.O-O  Bg7  7.c4  d6  8.Nc3  O-O  leads to Leningrad-like positions.   3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  g6  5.Nf3  d6  transposes to 3. Nf3     3.g4  fxg4  4.h3  g3!  a typical maneuver to avoid the opening of the h-file  5.fxg3  Usually White likes to play   5.Qxg3  here but in this variation the queen has to protect d4.  e5!  and Black is at least equal.     3.d5  Nb4  4.Qxf5   4.Qb3  e6!  5.dxe6  dxe6  6.Nc3  Nf6  leads to an equal position.  4...Nf6  threatens d6 and the queen cannot defend c2 any longer  5.Na3  c6!   5...Nbxd5  6.e4  d6  is about equal.  6.dxc6  d5  7.Qg5  Nxc6  gives Black plenty of compensation for the pawn. }
3... Nxd4
{ This is Black's only good move. But Black has to be willing to sacrifice a piece for a long lasting attack here. }
4. Qh5+
{ 4.Qd3  e5  5.Nf3   5.e3  Nc6  6.c4  Nf6  7.Nc3  Bb4  is about equal.  Nc6  6.e4  Nf6  is at least equal. If White's light-squared bishop could go to b5 we would get a position from the Jaenisch gambit in the Ruy lopez: 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5 4. d3 fxe5 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. Qd3 }
4... g6 5. Qe5 { This double attack is White's point. } 5... Nxc2+ 6. Kd1 Nf6
7. Kxc2 Bg7
{ The starting point of this variation. Black intends to play d5 and O-O in the next two moves. The order does not seem to matter much but starting with d5 seems to be more precise since after d5 the move Nh5 can be played in some lines. White's main defense is to put pressure on d5 with moves like Nc3, e4 or Nh3 and Nf4 so that Qxd5 is possible after discovered attacks on the queen by the knight.  This chapter contains too many lines on this piece sacrifice to remember them all. I would play through them to get a feeling for what the main ideas are but unless you have concrete reasons for believing the piece sacrifice will get on the board I would not spend too much time on these lines. I put them up in case you want to check what I suggest against a specific setup. }
