1. d4 f5 2. Qd3
{ In this chapter we look at Black's move 2... d5. If White plays quiet moves we get a Stonewall but with the unusual move Qd3. But in the majority of games White played 3. g4 after which we will transpose to lines from the 2. g4 chapter. Nonetheless, it is a good idea to have some rough guidelines on how to play the Stonewall just in case.  Before looking at these positions it is useful to have a summary of what to do in the regular Stonewall.      Black's pieces   - Black puts his pawns on f5, e6, d5, c6   - the dark-squared bishop usually goes to d6  (in older games e7 was more common)   - the light-squared bishop nowadays is mostly developed via b6, Bb7  (before Bd7-e8-h5 or g6 was more common)   - knight on g8: f6   - knight on b8: stays for a while on b8 especially if b6 is planned to protect c6. If White plays a4 then Na6 is also often good   - the pawn move c7-c6 can be delayed to take the sting out of the Bf4xd6 maneuver because after cxd6! the square e5 is no longer weak.   White's pieces   - light-squared bishop: usually g3 and Bg2, sometimes e3 and Bd3   - knight g1: usually f3 sometimes followed by Nf3-e5-d3 or Nf3-e1-d3, sometimes Nh3-f4-d3   - dark-squared bishop, often a3 or f4, trying to exchange Black's bishop on d6, sometimes b2   - knight on b1, stays for a while on b1 if White wants to play Ba3. Otherwise Nb1-d2-f3 is typical   key squares, typical manoeuvers, typical plans   - e5 is probably the most import square in the Stonewall. If White can control e5 with pieces then White is usually better. If White has to recapture with a pawn on e5 then Black has often equalized   - to increase the control of the dark squares  (especially e5)  White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops with Bf4  (not fearing Bxf4 gxf4)  or Ba3   - endgames with a white knight against Black's light-squared bishop tend to be good for White.   - Bd7-e8-h5 can be useful but if White manages to move his pieces in time then the bishop can be useless on h5   - after cxd5 by White Black usually wants to take back with the e-pawn, unless the light-squared bishop has been fianchettoed. In that case cxd5 is often better because the pawn on c6 can become weak }
