{ Sometimes White plays the move e4 after Nc3 or f3 or both. But if you remember to answer e4 with fxe4, f3 with d5 and Nc3 with Nf6 you are fine in all move orders. }
2... fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6
{ There are now three moves regularly played in this position. In increasing order of strength  (and popularity)  these moves are 4. g4 ?!, 4. f3 and 4. Bg5. The bishop move is the best and deserves its own chapter. 4.g4 is a bit dubious but has been played by strong players and shows up fairly regularly in Blitz. I doubt that White can fully equalize after 4. g4 if Black plays aggressively. 4. f3 is better and leads to equal positions without posing Black any problems. }
4. f3
{ 4.g4  threatens g5 and if White were able to push the pawn to g5 then Black would be in trouble. Fortunately, that is not possible.  4...h6!  Clearly the best move. If White plays g5 now then Black gets a better version of the standard Staunton Gambit because the half-open h-file is much more useful than the half-open g-file. Trying to prepare the pawn push with h4 does not work either because White's h-pawn will be pinned after hxg5  5.f3  d5  Now White has several options, 6.h3, 6.Bg2, 6.Bf4, 6.fxe4 but after h3 Black can put pressure on White's center with Nc6 and e5, after either of the bishop moves c5 is strong and after fxe4 White has problems with g4. }
4... d5
{ The reason why 4. f3 is not so strong. Black can play d5 immediately without having to fear Bxf6 and Qh5+. Black's plan is simple: Bf5, Nc6, Qd7 and O-O-O. If White plays Nge2 and Ng3 then protect the bishop with e6. If White plays Bc4 then Nc6-a5 is good as long as the bishop cannot retreat to e2. }
5. Bg5 Bf5 6. fxe4 dxe4 7. Nge2 e6 8. Ng3 Be7
{ The main line. Black has equalized and White has to put in some effort to regain the pawn. }
