1. d4 f5 2. e4 fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ The best move in my opinion. Black threatens to regain the pawn while preventing d5.   4...d5  5.Bxf6  exf6  6,  Qh5+  g6  7.Qxd5  is good for White.  The move d5 is important for Black because it supports the pawn on e4. The goal is not necessarily to keep the extra pawn but to make it more difficult for White to develop harmoniously. There are several lines in which a white knight on e2 blocks the bishop either from developing if the bishop is still on f1 or from retreating to e2 if attacked by Na5 if the bishop is on c4. }
4... g6
{ One of three popular moves  (the others are c6 and Nc6)  but currently my favorite. The point of this move is not to play Bg7, although sometimes the bishop goes to g7 later, but to prepare d5 which is not possible immediately because White has Bxf6, Qh5+ and Qxd5. }
5. h4
{ Objectively 5. f3 may be stronger but 5. h4 is certainly the most dangerous move where some knowledge is necessary. White's alternatives are   5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Nxe4  d5  and Black is already slighly better.   5.Bc4  c6  6.d5  Bg7  and Black gets a good game by attacking d5. For instance  7.Nge2  e6  8.dxe6  d5  and Bxe6.   5.f3  d5  6.fxe4   6.Qd2  Bg7  7.O-O-O  Nc6  8.Bb5  White can also transpose to 6. fxe4 with 8. fxe4 here.  O-O  9.fxe4  Nxe4  10.Nxe4  dxe4  with a balanced position.  Nxe4  I like this move because it sidesteps any later Bxf6.  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Bc4   8.Qd2  Bg7  9.O-O-O  Nc6  gives Black a good position.  Nc6  followed by Na5 gives Black a good position. }
5... d5 6. h5
{ The only dangerous move for Black. But Black is fine as long as he knows what he is doing. After other moves Black prepares castling queenside with Nc6, Bf5 and Qd7 or Qd6. }
6... Bf5
{ 6...Bg7?!  7.h6  Bf8  8.f3  is good for White.   6...Nxh5?  7.Rxh5  gxh5  8.Qxh5+  Kd7  9.Qf7  is close to losing for Black. }
7. Bxf6
{ Otherwise Black can play Qd6 and Nc6 and O-O-O with a small advantage. } 7...
exf6 8. g4
{ The point of White's last move. The pawn on g6 is no longer protected after the bishop retreats. }
8... Be6 { Protecting d5 and keeping the 7th rank for the queen. } 9. hxg6
{ This is White's idea. } 9... Qd7
{ The key move in this variation. This move  - protects h7   - prepares to castle long after Nc6  - prepares Qg7 to protect the rook on h8  - keeps an eye on d5  (Qe7 instead of Qd7 runs into Nxd5 in some lines)   - threatens g4 }
10. g5
{ After other moves Black can force the exchange of White's g-pawn and the Black's h-pawn with Qg7 after which the bishop pair and the protected passed pawn on e4 give Black an edge. One line worth knowing is   10.f4  Qg7!   10...exf3  11.Bd3!  is what White is hoping for  11.f5  hxg6!  12.Rxh8  Qxh8  13.fxe6  Qh4+  14.Ke2  Qh2+  regaining the piece with a clear advantage. }
10... fxg5
{ 10...Qg7  is also possible but this gives White the extra option  11.gxf6  which is fine for Black after Qxg6. }
11. Qh5 Bg7
{ 11...Qg7  is an ambitious alternative. Black protects the rook to threaten hxg6 and vacates the square d7 for the knight. But since the resulting variations are rather complicated it is only given as an alternative here. }
12. gxh7+ Qf7 13. Qxg5
{ 13.Qxf7  Kxf7  14.f3  Bxd4  15.fxe4  Bxc3  16.bxc3  dxe4  looks a bit better for Black.   13.Nb5  Na6  14.Qxg5  Bf6  15.Qg3  O-O-O!  is also good for Black. }
13... Nd7
{ Black has a good position. If necessary Black can play Bf6 to be able to castle or play Nf8 and Nxh7 to regain his pawn. }
