1. d4 f5 2. Nc3
{ White wants to play e4. If Black does nothing to stop this then White will get a good position. Black has two moves which stop White from playing e4 without sacrificing a pawn. My suggestion here is the less committal move Nf6. 2... d5 is playable but I dislike 3. Bf4 which gives White control of the dark squares in the center without getting anything in return. }
2... Nf6
{ 2...g6  This move is too dangerous. White can immediately attack with  3.h4  Even the simple   3.e4  fxe4  4.Nxe4  is better for White. The attack with h4-h5 can be kept in reserve.  Bg7  4.h5  followed by e4 is good for White.   2...d5  3.Bf4  This position may be playable but I don't see any active plans for Black. For example  3...e6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  Bb4  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.bxc3  followed by c4 and White is a bit better. }
3. Bg5 { White threatens e4 again. } 3... d5
{ Black weakens e5 but stops e4 and here the bishop is not so well placed on g5. Ne4 is often possible if White chooses a quieter setup and if White captures on f6 we have a pawn covering the e5 square. }
4. Bxf6
