1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 h6
{ 2...g6  This is a good and solid move but it has three disadvantages. There is quite a bit of theory, there are many transpositions, and finally, since it is the most common move in this position, White players are well-prepared for this move. Since I did not manage to reduce the number of variations to a reasonable level and since I play the less common 2... h6 at least as often as 2... g6, I decided to go with 2... h6.   2...Nf6  is also possible but I believe that White is better after  3.Bxf6  exf6  White gets an improved version of the 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 lines because c4 is still possible. For instance:  4.e3  d5  5.c4  This puts immediately pressure on Black's center. This is not possible in the aforementioned 2. Nc3 line because the knight blocks the c-pawn there. Black can try to keep a pawn on d5 with  5...c6  But now White can increase the pressure on d5 with  6.Nc3  followed by Qb3, cxd5 and Ne2-f4 or a queenside expansion with c5 and b4-b5. I do not trust Black's position here. }
3. Bh4
{ The only sensible alternative is Bf4 but then Black gets the free move h6 which is quite useful when the bishop is on f4. }
3... g5
{ Now White has three reasonable moves: Bg3, e3 and e4. The first two will usually lead by transposition to the same positions where White can fight for a small advantage. After e4 White is usually willing to sacrifice the bishop in return for 2-3 pawns and attacking chances. }
4. e4
{ Not the strongest move but the most dangerous move to meet without preparation.   4.Bg3  d6  5.h4  5. e3 transposes to 4. e3  5...f4  is good for Black.   4.e3  The strongest move in my opinion.  Nf6  The most flexible move. Black stops the check on h5. Since d4 is well protected there is no need to hurry with Bg7. Sometimes it is also useful to protect g5 with Rg8 after a quick h4 by White.  5.Bg3  d6  restricting the bishop on g3.  6.h4  g4   6...Rg8  This is the move that Pruijssers suggests. It keeps the pawn duo f5 and g5 intact. However Black ends up in a rather passive position after the moves  7.hxg5  hxg5  8.Be2  e6   8...Be6  9.c4  Na6  is possible  (I have played it)  but can run into problems after a quick b4.  9.c4  I have spent a lot of time on this position but haven't found a path to an acceptable position for Black. Black has problems finding squares for his queenside pieces because Nc6 will always run sooner or later into d5. The check on h5 can also be a problem, for instance, after Ne4 by Black.  7.h5  The most principled move. White stops Nh5 and gains space on the kingside.   7.Ne2  Nh5  8.Nbc3  Bg7  gives Black enough counterplay. Black can castle to either side and the knight on b8 will probably go to f6 to replace the knight on h5 which will very likely be exchanged after Ne2-f4.  7...Be6  8.Ne2   8.Bd3  Qd7  preparing Bf7  9.c4  Bf7  10.Qb3  is a setup suggested by engines and played by correspondence players. Now Black has two choices: c6 followed by Na6 and Bg7, or ignoring the threat Qxb7 and just go Bg7.  Bg7  11.Nc3   11.Qxb7  O-O  12.Qxa8  c5  with a roughly balanced position because White will have to return the material to free his queen.  11...O-O  12.Nge2  Nc6  with mutual chances, the model games section contains an example.  8...Bf7  9.Nf4  Now Black has two interesting moves: Qd7 and Nc6. Often both moves will be played.  9...Qd7   9...Nc6  is interesting as well. But Black has to be prepared for  10.Bb5  a6  11.Bxc6  Starting with the queen move may look a bit artificial but it avoids the pin and the queen starts covering the potential weaknesses on f5 and e6.  I believe Black has enough counterplay in either case. The pawn on h5 may become a target and Black can still castle either way: Bg7 and O-O, or Qd7/Nc6 and O-O-O. }
4... Bg7
{ 4...Nf6  The best move after 4. e3 but now White has 5. e5  5.e5  e6  Black loses his knight but gets the bishop in return. The resulting positions are balanced. If you don't like the sharper positions after 4... Bg7 then this line is a reasonable alternative.  6.exf6   6.Bg3  f4  7.Bd3  This looks dangerous, but after the correct reply  7...d5  8.Bg6+  Kd7  Black is fine.  6...Qxf6  7.Bg3  f4  Black does not need to hurry with regaining his piece. Taking on g3 allows White to open the f- or h-file, so waiting until White loses a tempo with f3, h3 or h4 is safer. If White takes on f4 then Black is fine after gxf4 because the kingside will remain closed for a bit longer. }
5. Bg3 d6
{ I like the setup with Bg7 and d6 because it does not seem to be so well-known. Black gets easy equality or White has to sacrifice a piece for unclear compensation. If this looks too risky for you, have a look at the alternative 4... Nf6.   5...f4 ?  6.Bxf4  gxf4  7.Qh5+  Kf8  8.Qf5+  followed by e5 is good for White. }
