{ A slightly artificial but useful move. It protects the pawn on f5 and the weak square e6. It also does not allow White to play Bb5 immediately which is the strongest move after   9...Nc6 }
10. Nc3 Bg7
{ 10...Nc6  is also possible but White can still play Bb5 in one move.  11.Bb5  a6  12.Ba4   12.Bxc6  Qxc6  is fine for Black. The queen will probably retreat to d7 and after Bg7 Black can decide which way to castle.  12...e6  13.e4  fxe4  14.Bh4  looks better for White. }
11. Bd3
{ White has other options but play tends to be similar.   11.Bb5  c6  12.Bd3  is the engine recommendation. The idea is to stop Nc6 even at the cost of a tempo. I would probably play  12...Na6  or   12...O-O  with the idea e5.   11.Qd2  Nc6  12.O-O-O  a6  If Black plays O-O-O immediately the pin after Bb5 is a bit unpleasant. Now Black can play e6 and O-O-O or even b5 and O-O. In both cases the position is quite complex and Black's chances are not worse. }
11... Nc6
{ Black is fine. Black can castle either way and e5 is also possible. } *

